fix:
/**
 * Inserts nodes at the specified position in this element. Nodes can be inserted between siblings or at the beginning or end of the child list. If the node being added is already part of a tree, it is removed from its current location.
 *
 * @param index Index where to add the nodes. Negative indexes count backwards from end of the list (e.g., -1 means last item).
 * @param children Nodes to add.
 */
public void insertChildren(int index, Collection<? extends Node> children) {
    if (index < -size || index > size) {
        throw new IndexOutOfBoundsException("Index out of range");
    } else if (children == null || children.isEmpty()) {
        return;
    }
    // Ensure we have an array representation of our children collection
    Node[] childArray = children instanceof List ? ((List<? extends Node>) children).toArray(new Node[0]) : NodeUtil.collectionToArray(children);

    if (index < 0) {
        index += childNodes.size();
    }

    // Remove all existing nodes that might conflict with the supplied nodes
    for (Node child : childArray) {
        if (!child.hasChangedOwner()) {
            child.remove();
        }
    }

    boolean ownerDocumentDirty = !ownerDoc.equals(this);
    for (Node child : childArray) {
        if (!child.hasChangedOwner()) {
            reparentChild(child);
        }

        childNodes.add(index, child);
        ownerDocumentDirty |= child.ownerDocument!=null && !child.ownerDocument.equals(ownerDoc);
    }

    if (ownerDocumentDirty) {
        setChanged();
    }
    reindexChildren();
}

issue_description:
When using org.jsoup.nodes.Element.insertChildren(int, Collection<? extends Node>) to move (more than one!) child-elements from one parent-element to the same parent, but different index then it produces wrong results.
The problem is that the first Element's 'move' leaves the siblingIndex unchanged and then the second 'move' removes a wrong element and produces some crap. Maybe calling reindexChildren() inside the loop in addChildren() fixes this.
Version 1.8.3.
Workaround: call remove() on the elements before passing them to insertChildren()
Easy Test Case:
    @Test
    public void mustCorrectlyMoveChildrenInsideOneParentElement() {

        Document doc = new Document( "" );
        Element body = doc.appendElement( "body" );
        body.appendElement( "div1" );
        body.appendElement( "div2" );
        Element div3 = body.appendElement( "div3" );
        Element div4 = body.appendElement( "div4" );

        ArrayList<Element> toMove = new ArrayList<Element>() {
            {
                add( div3 );
                add( div4 );
            }
        };

        body.insertChildren( 0, toMove );

        String result = doc.toString().replaceAll( "\\s+", "" );
        assertEquals( "<body><div3></div3><div4></div4><div1></div1><div2></div2></body>", result );

    }

